heading: Planning
content: The group met and collectively took decisions about different things. Different team members were given different duties to read the documentation/datasheets of the various components to be used. They were also told learning which topics would help them to contribute to this project.

heading: Buying things
content: We went to Jatni to buy Aluminium box pipes (Rs450/10ft) for the arms of the drone. We used switchboard plates (Sunmica) (Rs 120) for the upper and lower plates which will hold the metal arms in place. We also had to buy screws, nuts and bolts of different sizes. We also went to Bhubaneshwar once (later) to buy small screws and special rubber spacers for soft-mounting the flight controller.

heading: Basic Structure Built
content: Four equal-sized (~24cm) pieces were cut off from the long aluminium pipe for the arms. Holes were drilled into measured places of appropriate diameter. We took the help of the Central Worksop for drilling holes due to the unavailability of those appropriately sized drill bits in RTC. Later we bought those drill bits ourselves. We also cut 2 pieces of Sunmica, each of dimension 13*13cm. We drilled holes into it in appropriate positions. Then we attached the metal arms to the plates. We used two 1.5inch long M6 bolts for each arm (which makes up 8 nuts &bolts).

heading: Motors Attached
content: EMAX Multicopter motor were attached to each of the arms of the drone frame. No additional holes for accomodating the back part of the main motor shaft other than for fixing the screws, in order to maintain structural rigidity. Additional spacers were built using 3D printers to ensure the back of the shaft does not touches the arm. Each motor weighs 53 grams and is able to provide maximum thrust of 860 grams.

heading: Construction of drone landing gear
content: The landing gears were designed using Solidworks and were constructed using 3D printer. The landing gear have unconventional truss based design framework (interior consisting of triangles) in order to provide critical mechanical rigidity with less material use. It consists of two parts which are to be fixed at the drone arms and are to be connected using screws. An advantage is that the distance between the landing gears is customizable and can be changed according to the payload characteristics.

heading: Drone assembly part 1
content: The assembly of the basic structure of the drone was done, starting from preparing Electronic Speed Controllers (ESC) by soldering with connecting wires (low gauge copper wire with ability to handle current upto 20-25 A). Motors were attached with connecting wires and the fixing sockets were insulated by winding and heat-shrinking rubber strips. The Power supply module was also prepared for mounting by soldering with connecting wires

heading: Drone assembly part 2
content: The power supply unit was fixed to the center of the base, and screwed using additional 3D printed hexagonal spacers over the fixing points. A carbon fibre made anti-vibration shock absorber was fixed on the spacers in order to soft mount the flight controller to be attached above it. All connections between the motors and the ESCs in each arm, and the power supply were completed with the wires organized using nylon cable zip ties.
